===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er}}

# {{label|en|archaic}} [[pitiable|Pitiable]]; deserving of [[compassion]]; [[helpless]].
#* '''1590''', {{w|Edmund Spenser}}, ''{{w|The Faerie Queene}}'', I.vi:
#*: A '''silly''' man, in simple weedes forworne, / And soild with dust of the long dried way; / His sandales were with toilesome trauell torne, / And face all tand with scorching sunny ray {{...}}
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: After long storms {{...}} with which my '''silly''' bark was tossed sore.
#* {{w|Samuel Taylor Coleridge}} (1772-1834)
#*: The '''silly''' buckets on the deck.
# {{label|en|obsolete}} [[simple|Simple]], [[unsophisticated]], [[ordinary]]; [[rustic]], [[ignorant]].
#* '''1633''', {{w|John Donne}}, "Sapho to Philænis":
#*: For, if we justly call each '''silly''' ''man'' / A ''little island'', What shall we call thee than?
#* {{w|William Shakespeare}} (1564-1616)
#*: A fourth man, in a '''silly''' habit.
#* {{w|John Milton}} (1608-1674)
#*: All that did their '''silly''' thoughts so busy keep.
# [[foolish|Foolish]], showing a [[lack]] of good [[sense]] and [[wisdom]]; [[frivolous]], [[trifling]].
#: {{usex|lang=en|I made a very '''silly''' mistake.}}
#: {{usex|lang=en|The newlyweds called each other '''silly''' little nicknames.}}
# [[irresponsible|Irresponsible]], showing irresponsible behaviors.
#: {{usex|lang=en|What a '''silly''' kid, he's always getting in trouble.}}
# [[semiconscious|Semiconscious]], [[witless]].
#: {{usex|lang=en|The impact of the ball knocked him '''silly'''.}}
# {{label|en|cricket}} Of a [[fielding]] [[position]], very [[close]] to the [[batsman]]; closer than [[short]].
# {{label|en|pejorative|lang=en}} [[simple|Simple]], not [[intelligent]], [[unrefined]].
#: {{usex|lang=en|John was prosperous and his helpless, '''silly''' father could be of no use to him.}}
#* {{quote-book|year=1935|author=[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/288354.George_Goodchild George Goodchild]
|title=Death on the Centre Court|chapter=1
|passage=“Anthea hasn't a notion in her head but to vamp a lot of '''silly''' mugwumps. She's set her heart on that tennis bloke{{...}}whom the papers are making such a fuss about.”}}
# {{label|en|obsolete}} Happy; fortunate; blessed.
#: {{rfquotek|Chaucer}}
# {{label|en|obsolete}} Harmless; innocent; inoffensive.
#* {{w|Edmund Spenser}} (c.1552–1599)
#*: The '''silly''' virgin strove him to withstand.
#* Robynson (More's Utopia)
#*: A '''silly''', innocent hare murdered of a dog.

